   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "An auto insurance company has collected some data about its customers including their demographics, education, employment, policy details, vehicle information on which insurance policy is, and claim amounts. You will help the senior management with some business questions that will help them to better understand their customers, improve their services, and improve profitability.\n",
    "\n",
    "Some business Objectives:\n",
    "\n",
    "Retain customers,\n",
    "Analyze relevant customer data,\n",
    "Develop focused customer retention programs.\n",
    "Based on the analysis, take targeted actions to increase profitable customer response, retention, and growth."
   ]
  },

    "#Load the continuous and discrete variables into continuous_df and discrete_df variables.\n",

    "\n",
    "# create df for continuous & discrete values\n",

   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 32,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "#From solutions:\n",
    "\n",
    "# Create function to print barplots from discrete data\n",
    "\n",
    "def df_bar(df):\n",
    "    sns.set(rc={'figure.figsize':(16,8)})\n",
    "    for i, col in enumerate(df):\n",
    "        plt.figure(i)\n",
    "        sns.barplot(x = df[col].value_counts().index, y = df[col].value_counts())\n",
    "        \n",
    "    plt.show()\n",
    "\n",
    "#The enumerate() method adds counter to an iterable and returns it (the enumerate object).\n",
    "# https://www.tutorialspoint.com/enumerate-in-python"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 33,

    "#Do the same with continuous variables (be careful, \n",
    "#you may change the plot type to another one better suited for continuous data).\n",
    "#What can you see in the plots?\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",

   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "#from the solutions\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "#for  visualization\n",
    "\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import seaborn as sns\n",
    "from matplotlib.colors import BASE_COLORS\n",
    "\n",
    "%matplotlib inline\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "def df_hist(df):\n",
    "    sns.set(rc={'figure.figsize':(16,8)})\n",
    "    for i, col in enumerate(df):\n",
    "        plt.figure(i)\n",
    "        sns.distplot(df[col], color = list(BASE_COLORS.keys())[i])\n",
    "        \n",
    "    plt.show()\n",
    "    \n",
    "    \n"
   ]
  },

    "f, axes = plt.subplots(int(categorical.shape[1] / 2), 2, figsize=(18, 50))\n",
    "\n",
    "for i, col in enumerate(categorical):\n",
    "\n",
    "    sns.barplot(x = categorical[col].value_counts().index,\n",
    "                y = categorical[col].value_counts(),\n",
    "                ax=axes[int(i / 2)][int(i) % 2])  \n",
    "    axes[int(i / 2)][int(i) % 2].set_title(col, fontsize = 14)\n",
    "    axes[int(i / 2)][int(i) % 2].set_ylabel(\"\")\n",

    "plt.show()"
   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 60,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "#response, employment status, vehicle class seem imbalanced. i would group them a lot more before encoding them"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "from the solutions:\n",
    "\n",
    "Education, employment status, policy and vehicle class are somewhat unbalanced. \\\n",
    "For education we could turn it into a binary variable (college +-), but i wouldnt touch it. \\\n",
    "Policy is redundant, may be we can classify it in L1, L2 and L3 groups \\\n",
    "I'd concatenate luxury suv, sports car and luxury car into luxury or among the other classes. \\\n",
    "For employment we could divide them among employed, unemployed and inactive. \\\n",
    "We can see that having open complains isn't that common so we can turn it into a binary variable, open not open \\\n",
    "For the number of policies we could join use 1, 2, 3, 4+"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": []
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 61,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "#There might be some columns that seem to be redundant, check their values to be sure. \n",
    "#What should we do with them?\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 62,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [

   "source": [
    "# we could group them, \n",
    "#either into L1,L2,L3 or into personal, corporate, special (but this would be redundant with policy type)\n",
    "#group into L1,L2,L3\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "#Create Look-Up list\n",
    "L1 = ['Personal L1','Corporate L1', 'Special L1']\n",
    "L2 = ['Personal L2','Corporate L2', 'Special L2']\n",
    "L3 = ['Personal L3','Corporate L3', 'Special L3']\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 66,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "def group(x):\n",
    "    if x in L1 :\n",
    "        return 'L1'\n",
    "    elif x in L2:\n",
    "        return 'L2'\n",
    "    else:\n",
    "        return 'L3'\n",
    "\n",
    "categoricals['Policy'] = pd.Series(list(map(group, categoricals['Policy'])))\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 84,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "#We will start with removing outliers. So far, we have discussed different methods to remove outliers. \n",
    "\n",
    "#Use the one you feel more comfortable with, define a function for that. #\n",
    "#Use the function to remove the outliers and apply it to the dataframe.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "already did that in line 41.\n",
    "\n",
    "other approach, from the solutions:\n",
    "    \n",
    "    remove outliers (normalization method)\n",
    "def outliers(column, threshold = 3):\n",
    "    data = column[abs(column.apply(lambda x: (x - column.mean()) / column.var() ** (1/2))) > threshold]\n",
    "    return data\n",
    "\n",
    "#Return the absolute value of the argument.\n",
    "#why threshold = 3 ?\n",
    "\n",
    "CLV_outliers = outliers(customer_df[\"customer_lifetime_value\"])\n",
    "MPA_outliers = outliers(customer_df[\"monthly_premium_auto\"])\n",
    "\n",
    "to_drop = CLV_outliers.index | MPA_outliers.index # Union\n",
    "\n",
    "#what is .index() used for here? "
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "#from solutions:\n",
    "\n",
    "#count_var is what exactly and why is it turned into a series?\n",
    "\n",
    "for cont_var in continuous:\n",
    "    maximum = copy_df[cont_var].max()\n",
    "    minimum = copy_df[cont_var].min()\n",
    "    clean_customer_df[cont_var] = clean_customer_df[cont_var].apply(lambda x: (x - minimum) / (maximum - minimum))\n",
    "    \n",
    "#however plotting this into graphs, it doesn't look very normalized to me"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": []
  },

    "#Encode the categorical variables\n",
    "\n",
    "#Since the model will only accept numerical data, check and make sure that every column is numerical, \n",
    "#if some are not, change it using encoding.\n",
    "#Hint for Categorical Variables\n",
    "#You should deal with the categorical variables as shown below \n",
    "#(for ordinal encoding, dummy code has been provided as well):\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# One hot to state\n",
    "# Ordinal to coverage\n",
    "# Ordinal to employmentstatus\n",
    "# Ordinal to location code\n",
    "# One hot to marital status\n",
    "# One hot to policy type\n",
    "# One hot to policy\n",
    "# One hot to renew offercustomer_df\n",
    "# One hot to sales channel\n",
    "# One hot vehicle class\n",
    "# Ordinal vehicle size\n",
    "\n",
    "#data[\"coverage\"] = data[\"coverage\"].map({\"Basic\" : 0, \"Extended\" : 1, \"Premium\" : 2})\n",
    "# given that column \"coverage\" in the dataframe \"data\" has three categories:\n",
    "# \"basic\", \"extended\", and \"premium\" and values are to be represented in the same order."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#what is ordinal encoding and when do you use it?\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "In ordinal encoding, each unique category value is assigned an integer value.\n",
    "\n",
    "For example, red is 1, green is 2, and blue is 3.\n",
    "\n",
    "https://machinelearningmastery.com/one-hot-encoding-for-categorical-data/"
   ]
  },

    "df_encode[\"Coverage\"] = df_encode[\"Coverage\"].map({\"Basic\" : 0, \"Extended\" : 1, \"Premium\" : 2})\n",
    "df_encode[\"EmploymentStatus\"] = df_encode[\"EmploymentStatus\"].map({\"Unemployed\" : 0, \"Inactive\" : 1, \"Employed\" : 2})\n",
    "df_encode[\"Location_Code\"] = df_encode[\"Location_Code\"].map({\"Rural\" : 0, \"Suburban\" : 1, \"Urban\" : 2})\n",

   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder \n",
    "  \n",
    "le = LabelEncoder() \n",
    "\n",
    "#for each columnc, label encoder accepts 1d arrays\n",
    "\n",
    "df_ohe= le.fit_transform(df_ohe)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 136,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "#other approach\n",
    "\n",
    "# importing one hot encoder from sklearn \n",
    "from sklearn.preprocessing import OneHotEncoder \n",
    "from sklearn.compose import ColumnTransformer \n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# creating one hot encoder object with categorical feature 0 \n",
    "# indicating the first column \n",
    "columnTransformer = ColumnTransformer([('encoder', \n",
    "                                        OneHotEncoder(), \n",
    "                                        [0])], \n",
    "                                      remainder='passthrough') \n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "  \n",
    "# creating one hot encoder object by default \n",
    "# entire data passed is one hot encoded \n",
    "onehotencoder = OneHotEncoder() \n",
    "  \n",
    "ohe = np.array(columnTransformer.fit_transform(df_ohe), dtype = np.str)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "#other approach\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "#example of a one hot encoding\n",
    "from numpy import asarray\n",
    "from sklearn.preprocessing import OneHotEncoder\n",
    "\n",
    "#define one hot encoding, check if this is the right configuration\n",
    "encoder = OneHotEncoder(sparse=False)\n",
    "\n",
    "#transform data\n",
    "onehot = encoder.fit_transform(ohe)\n",
    "print(onehot)\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },

    "\n",
    "It takes a feature matrix X_test and the expected target values y_test. Predictions for X_test are compared with y_test and either accuracy (for classifiers) or R score (for regression estimators is returned."
   ]

   "source": [
    "def models_automation(models, X_train, y_train):\n",
    "    for model in models:\n",
    "        model.fit(X_train, y_train)\n",
    "        print(f\"{model.__class__.__name__}: Train -> {model.score(X_train, y_train)}, Test -> {model.score(X_test, y_test)}\")\n"
   ]
  },
